      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for both heating and cooling assistance in the same year?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can receive one heating payment and one cooling payment per year. The maximum is $580 for heating and $520 for cooling, though actual amounts depend on your income, household size, and energy costs."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my utility bill is in my landlord's name, not mine?",
          "answer": "You can still qualify if you live in government housing by providing your lease agreement instead of a utility bill in your name. For private rentals, check with your local Community Action Agency about alternative documentation."
        },
        {
          "question": "How quickly can I get help if my power is about to be shut off?",
          "answer": "Crisis assistance can provide emergency help with a disconnection notice, but you must contact your local Community Action Agency immediately. Crisis payments can be up to $1,100 for heating or $990 for cooling emergencies."
        },
        {
          "question": "Why can't I apply online directly to the state?",
          "answer": "Alabama LIHEAP is administered entirely through local Community Action Agencies in each county. There is no central state application. You must find and contact your county's specific agency to apply."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does LIHEAP pay my entire utility bill?",
          "answer": "No, LIHEAP payments are applied to your utility account, but you remain responsible for any remaining balance. Think of it as partial assistance, not full coverage of energy costs."
        },
        {
          "question": "If I'm 62 years old, do I get priority even if my income is higher?",
          "answer": "Age 60+ gives you priority for appointments and processing, but you still must meet the income limits (150% of federal poverty level). Priority doesn't override income requirements, it just means you're served first among eligible applicants."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my adult child apply for LIHEAP on my behalf?",
          "answer": "Yes, but they must provide a signed statement indicating they are applying as a second party and bring all required documents including your photo ID and Social Security card."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if I apply late in the season when funds are running low?",
          "answer": "LIHEAP operates on first-come, first-served basis until funds are exhausted. If your local agency runs out of money, you cannot receive assistance until the next program year. Apply as early as possible when applications open."
        }
      ],
